Description: Limestone figure of a woman during child-birth. Simple triangular votive plaque with a roughly carved naked pregnant woman. Also known as a ‘baubo’ figure. Carved from soft limestone. Missing right foot.
Curator's comments: These child-birth plaques were common in Naukratis (Petrie 1886, 40, pl.19.4; Gutch in Hogarth 1899, 82, see notes for nos. 49-56; Hogarth 1905, 127-9, Fig. 8a; British Museum 1965,0930.954; Cairo TR20/9/27/25) and attributed to Naukratis (Cambridge E.SU.146). Such figure plaques were discovered by Hogarth in the northwest corner of the Great Temenos, in '6th century' deposits and were also ‘common’ in 6th century deposits around the town (Edgar in Gutch et al. 1905, 128-129, pl.8a). Petrie dated them to the 6th and 4th century BC (Petrie 1886, 40, pl.19.4). Parallels are known from Kom el Zalat, near Damenhur (Cairo SR5/6442), Memphis (Petrie Museum UC38346) and acquired in Alexandria (Cairo SR5/6490).
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (CE.037) (Phase 2)
